metadata.name: Strata #42
metadata.description:
A generative series inspired by the work of Vera Molnár, Strata explores the diversity that can come from one shape - the simple rectangle.

With 16 properties and ~600 palettes, I hope that each mint offers something unique and special.

Exploration is fully open and will be left open post-mint :)

metadata.name: Reading a book #551
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Broken Dither #11
metadata.description:
This is ordered dithering gone awry.

Click or press space to pause.

By default, it runs at native screen resolution.
A low-resolution mode can be toggled by pressing 'L'.

Made with a fragment shader in WebGL
fx(hash) genesis Generative Token by loackme

metadata.name: PRINTERS #199
metadata.description:
Generative animated artwork made using shader feedback and pixel quantization.

PRINTERS is a study of rasterized type and bitmap imagery. It builds on the tradition of ASCII and typographic art, blending dithering techniques with chunky, pixelated glyphs. Here, the movement and blending of color is interpreted as a monochrome composition of recognizable pixel patterns taken from legacy video games and operating systems. What appears as typography is actually a custom set of 8x8 pixel patterns rendered in a GLSL shader that produces a conceptual tension between low-res graphics and high-power GPU computation.

PRINTERS is designed to be both viewed on a screen and printed on office paper with a home/office inkjet printer.

Press 'i' to invert the colors.
Press '1', '2', or '3' to scale the bitmap glyphs.
Press 'g' to download a looping animated GIF (90 frames).
Press 's' to capture a single frame.
Press 'f' (or double tap in mobile) to stretch to full screen.
Made with vanilla javascript and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: Endless Ridge #92
metadata.description:
Generative scene programmed by GLSL, continuously changing its form with time.
Plenty of them maintain minimal with monotone,
some of them varied as light shined on them from time to time,
some of them are veiled with mist and clouds,
and few of them reflected silver light with special textures.

Minted one piece then you’ll own one view to observe.

Created by Natalie.J

metadata.name: Kaibō #138
metadata.description:
What would happen if we took the natural forms that surround us and dissected them into composable shapes? 

Taking the organic world of Yashinoki, Kiabō dissects organic forms into composable elements, then reforms them into precise geometric arrangements. These shapes give way to random, organic growth the closer we look at them. 


Controls in live mode:
- Press [s] to save a png

metadata.name: Complicare #34
metadata.description:
Complicare is my first "still" generative work, and an exercise in minimalism.

Inspired by pioneers like Sol Lewitt and Frank Stella, as well as current fx_hash artists such as Rev Dan Catt and Yazid, this work attempts to balance a diverse visual output with a restricted generative system. I also wanted to focus on honing my abilities to add texture to the digital canvas, taking cues from other great artists on here like William Mapan and Hevey.

Each piece has one of 17 different layouts and one of 6 different color palettes.

Thanks to all of the artists on fx_hash for inspiring me every day to make more art, and particularly to dcarcher for some really insightful artistic perspective and feedback.

metadata.name: Mirror Mirror #61
metadata.description:
Stare into the abyss with endlessly repeating forms twisting into the infinity defined by perlin randomness. This project is inspired by early childhood memories looking into two mirrors and playing with reflections forever.

Mirror Mirror is a generative project with a digital output, but it has a second life as a physical IRL object that can be cut from 12 layers of wood or plotted on paper.

24 free physicals will be attached at random to mints.
Learn more about physicals: https://alleditions.art/p/mirrormirror

SPECIAL FEATURES
- Shift-P: exports a PNG
- Shift-E: explodes the layers
- Shift-S: Exports an SVG
- A, S, D, & W: skew the layers
- ?screws=true: add some holes for Chicago screws

metadata.name: miniGlyph #144
metadata.description:
In celebration of #tezos4tezos I am releasing this mini version of a more complex work in progress. 

Every 24th mint (ex: 1, 24, 48, 72, etc) will receive a free physical woodcut.
https://alleditions.art/p/miniglyph

This project is designed such that it can export a layered vector SVG that can be used for plotting or cutting out of wood with a laser or paper with a Cricut.

Shift P - Export a PNG
Shift S - Export an SVG
Shift E - explode the layers

metadata.name: Ray Drops #100
metadata.description:
Ray Drops plays with the idea of rays that are projected out from a random center point which oscillate at variable frequencies. At each inflection point it has a chance of being intersected by a ring. The inflection points vary in how closely they are spaced and can cluster around the center point or fan all the way out to the edges. 

When run this generative creates a 12 layer SVG vector that is designed to be run on a laser cutter in order to build an in real life woodcut. Each layer is a single contiguous piece with no floating elements so when cut out of wood you end up with 12 layers that can be secured with 10 Chicago screws.  

Learn more and get physical editions: https://alleditions.art/p/ray-drops

Shift P - exports a PNG
Shift S - exports SVG
Shift E - explodes the layers

The 5 rarest mints (once the series is minted out) will receive a free signed physical which can be claimed by an owner of the NFT at anytime. It can be left attached and claimed by any future owner. 

I will also be giving away 5 free signed physicals randomly to people who tweet a picture of their edition and tag @shawnkemp

metadata.name: Over the Air #584
metadata.description:
During the last couple of decades, over the air television signals and antennas switched to digital, bringing with them a new form of static and distortion as the signal is broken up. "Over the Air" is inspired by these digital distortions, incorporating aspects of them into the same grid-like structure seen on the television. Additional patterns are combined in the grid with these distortions to create the final artwork.

Patterns for the individual blocks in the grid are divided into categories, and various amounts are picked for each work, with dozens of possible mixtures. Patterns can flow in different directions across the varied canvases. Distribution of these patterns across the grid varies from work to work, providing for different feels as they bunch together or spread apart.
